### [Proverbs Chapter 10](../../../bib/kjv/pro010.htm#001.md)

[Proverbs 10:1](../../../bib/kjv/pro010.htm#001.md)

<span class="margnote"><span id="an_001">pro 10:1</span></span>

Here begins the second part of the book, Pro. 10:1-22:16, which, with
the third, Pro. 22:16-25:28, contains series of proverbs whose sense is
complete in one or two verses, and which, having no logical connection,
admit of no analysis. The parallelisms of Pro. 10:1-15:33 are mostly
antithetic; and those of Pro. 16:1-22:16, synthetic. The evidences of
art in the structure are very clear, and indicate, probably, a purpose
of facilitating the labor of memorizing. (Pro. 10:1-32)

wise \[and\] foolish--as they follow or reject the precepts of wisdom.

maketh . . . father--or, "gladdens a father."

heaviness--or, "grief."

[Proverbs 10:2](../../../bib/kjv/pro010.htm#002.md)

<span class="margnote"><span id="an_002">pro 10:2</span></span>

Treasures . . . nothing--that is, Ill-gotten gains give no true
happiness (compare [Pro 4:17](../../../bib/kjv/pro004.htm#017.md); [Mat
6:19](../../../bib/kjv/mat006.htm#019).md).

righteousness--especially beneficence ([Psa
112:9](../../../bib/kjv/psa112.htm#009).md).

death--the greatest of all evils.

[Proverbs 10:3](../../../bib/kjv/pro010.htm#003.md)

<span class="margnote"><span id="an_003">pro 10:3</span></span>

(Compare [Psa 37:16-20](../../../bib/kjv/psa037.htm#016).md). The last
clause is better: "He will repel the greedy desires of the wicked."

[Proverbs 10:4](../../../bib/kjv/pro010.htm#004.md)

<span class="margnote"><span id="an_004">pro 10:4</span></span>

slack--literally, "deceitful," failing of its purpose (compare [Hos
7:16](../../../bib/kjv/hos007.htm#016).md).

maketh rich--(compare [Pro 10:22](../../../bib/kjv/pro010.htm#022).md).

[Proverbs 10:5](../../../bib/kjv/pro010.htm#005.md)

<span class="margnote"><span id="an_005">pro 10:5</span></span>

son--as [Pro 1:8](../../../bib/kjv/pro001.htm#008.md), [Pro
1:10](../../../bib/kjv/pro001.htm#010.md), and often.

sleepeth--in indolence, and not for rest.

causeth shame--literally, "is base" (compare [Pro
14:35](../../../bib/kjv/pro014.htm#035.md); [Pro
17:2](../../../bib/kjv/pro017.htm#002).md).

[Proverbs 10:6](../../../bib/kjv/pro010.htm#006.md)

<span class="margnote"><span id="an_006">pro 10:6</span></span>

Blessings--literally, "Praises." The last clause is better: "The mouth
of the wicked covereth (or concealeth) violence (or mischievous
devices)" to be executed in due time ([Psa
5:9](../../../bib/kjv/psa005.htm#009.md); [Psa
10:7](../../../bib/kjv/psa010.htm#007.md); [Rom
3:14](../../../bib/kjv/rom003.htm#014).md), and hence has no praises
(compare [Pro 10:11](../../../bib/kjv/pro010.htm#011).md).

[Proverbs 10:7](../../../bib/kjv/pro010.htm#007.md)

<span class="margnote"><span id="an_007">pro 10:7</span></span>

blessed--literally, "for a blessing," or praise.

shall rot--literally, "be worm-eaten," useless and disgusting.

[Proverbs 10:8](../../../bib/kjv/pro010.htm#008.md)

<span class="margnote"><span id="an_008">pro 10:8</span></span>

wise, &c.--(compare [Pro 9:8-9](../../../bib/kjv/pro009.htm#008.md), [Pro
9:16](../../../bib/kjv/pro009.htm#016).md), opposed to

prating fool--or, "fool of lips of wicked language."

fall--headlong, suddenly.

[Proverbs 10:9](../../../bib/kjv/pro010.htm#009.md)

<span class="margnote"><span id="an_009">pro 10:9</span></span>

perverteth his ways--acts deceitfully.

known--discovered and punished.

[Proverbs 10:10](../../../bib/kjv/pro010.htm#010.md)

<span class="margnote"><span id="an_010">pro 10:10</span></span>

Two vices contrasted; hypocrisy, or insinuating evil against one ([Pro
6:13](../../../bib/kjv/pro006.htm#013.md); [Psa
35:19](../../../bib/kjv/psa035.htm#019).md), and rashness of speech. In
each case, the results are on the evildoers.

[Proverbs 10:11](../../../bib/kjv/pro010.htm#011.md)

<span class="margnote"><span id="an_011">pro 10:11</span></span>

a well--or, "source" of good to himself and others ([Joh
7:37-38](../../../bib/kjv/joh007.htm#037).md). On last clause, see on [Pro
10:6](../../../bib/kjv/pro010.htm#006.md).

[Proverbs 10:12](../../../bib/kjv/pro010.htm#012.md)

<span class="margnote"><span id="an_012">pro 10:12</span></span>

strifes--or, "litigations."

covereth--by forgiveness and forbearance.

[Proverbs 10:13](../../../bib/kjv/pro010.htm#013.md)

<span class="margnote"><span id="an_013">pro 10:13</span></span>

In the lips . . . found--hence, not beaten, as the wicked-speaking fool.

void of understanding-- ([Pro 6:32](../../../bib/kjv/pro006.htm#032.md);
[Pro 7:7](../../../bib/kjv/pro007.htm#007).md).

[Proverbs 10:14](../../../bib/kjv/pro010.htm#014.md)

<span class="margnote"><span id="an_014">pro 10:14</span></span>

lay up knowledge--that is, as treasures for good use.

mouth . . . destruction--or, "as to the mouth," &c., destruction is
near; they expose themselves to evil by prating.

[Proverbs 10:15](../../../bib/kjv/pro010.htm#015.md)

<span class="margnote"><span id="an_015">pro 10:15</span></span>

Both by trusting in "uncertain riches" ([Ti1
6:17](../../../bib/kjv/ti1006.htm#017).md), or by the evils of poverty
([Pro 30:9](../../../bib/kjv/pro030.htm#009).md), men, not fearing God,
fall into dangers.

[Proverbs 10:16](../../../bib/kjv/pro010.htm#016.md)

<span class="margnote"><span id="an_016">pro 10:16</span></span>

The industry of the righteous is alone truly successful, while the
earnings of the wicked tempt and lead to sin.

[Proverbs 10:17](../../../bib/kjv/pro010.htm#017.md)

<span class="margnote"><span id="an_017">pro 10:17</span></span>

keepeth--observes ([Pro 3:18](../../../bib/kjv/pro003.htm#018.md); [Pro
4:22](../../../bib/kjv/pro004.htm#022).md).

refuseth--or, "turns from reproof," which might direct him aright.

[Proverbs 10:18](../../../bib/kjv/pro010.htm#018.md)

<span class="margnote"><span id="an_018">pro 10:18</span></span>

Both vices must one day be known and punished, and hence their folly.

[Proverbs 10:19](../../../bib/kjv/pro010.htm#019.md)

<span class="margnote"><span id="an_019">pro 10:19</span></span>

Much speech involves risk of sin; hence the wisdom of restraining the
tongue ([Psa 39:1](../../../bib/kjv/psa039.htm#001.md); [Jam
1:26](../../../bib/kjv/jam001.htm#026).md).

[Proverbs 10:20](../../../bib/kjv/pro010.htm#020.md)

<span class="margnote"><span id="an_020">pro 10:20</span></span>

Right speech is the fruit of a good heart, but the wicked show theirs to
be useless.

[Proverbs 10:21](../../../bib/kjv/pro010.htm#021.md)

<span class="margnote"><span id="an_021">pro 10:21</span></span>

Fools not only fail to benefit others, as do the righteous, but procure
their own ruin (compare [Pro 10:11](../../../bib/kjv/pro010.htm#011.md),
[Pro 10:17](../../../bib/kjv/pro010.htm#017.md); [Hos
4:6](../../../bib/kjv/hos004.htm#006).md).

[Proverbs 10:22](../../../bib/kjv/pro010.htm#022.md)

<span class="margnote"><span id="an_022">pro 10:22</span></span>

it maketh, &c.--"it" is emphatic. Riches from God are without the sorrow
of ill-gotten wealth (compare [Ecc
2:21-23](../../../bib/kjv/ecc002.htm#021.md); [Ti1
6:9-10](../../../bib/kjv/ti1006.htm#009.md), [Ti1
6:17](../../../bib/kjv/ti1006.htm#017).md).

[Proverbs 10:23](../../../bib/kjv/pro010.htm#023.md)

<span class="margnote"><span id="an_023">pro 10:23</span></span>

Sin is the pleasure of the wicked; wisdom that of the good.

